 {"id":"bd-33rg","title":"Design RFC: Mutex poison handling patterns","description":"## Task Description

Write a design document (as code comments or internal doc) defining the mutex poison handling strategy for rich_rust.

## Deliverables

1. Document in `src/sync.rs` or `src/lib.rs` explaining:
   - Why mutex poisoning happens (thread panic while holding lock)
   - The chosen recovery strategy
   - When to use each helper function
   - Examples of proper usage

2. Decision on strategy:

   **Option A: Always Recover**
   ```rust
   fn lock_or_recover<T>(mutex: &Mutex<T>) -> MutexGuard<T> {
       mutex.lock().unwrap_or_else(|e| e.into_inner())
   }
   ```
   Pros: Never panics, always makes progress
   Cons: May use corrupted state

   **Option B: Recover with Logging**
   ```rust
   fn lock_or_log<T>(mutex: &Mutex<T>, ctx: &str) -> Option<MutexGuard<T>> {
       match mutex.lock() {
           Ok(guard) => Some(guard),
           Err(e) => {
               eprintln\!("[WARN] Mutex poisoned at {ctx}, recovering");
               Some(e.into_inner())
           }
       }
   }
   ```
   Pros: Observability, can track down issues
   Cons: Slight overhead, logs noise

   **Option C: Feature-gated Debug Logging**
   ```rust
   #[cfg(debug_assertions)]
   fn lock_debug<T>(mutex: &Mutex<T>, ctx: &str) -> MutexGuard<T> {
       mutex.lock().unwrap_or_else(|e| {
           eprintln\!("[DEBUG] Mutex poison at {ctx}");
           e.into_inner()
       })
   }
   #[cfg(not(debug_assertions))]
   fn lock_debug<T>(mutex: &Mutex<T>, _ctx: &str) -> MutexGuard<T> {
       mutex.lock().unwrap_or_else(|e| e.into_inner())
   }
   ```
   Pros: Zero overhead in release, debug visibility
   Cons: More complex

## Recommendation

Option B with #[cfg(debug_assertions)] for logging, keeping release builds clean.

